metadata.name: Stepping Stones #696
metadata.description:
"Stepping Stones" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022

Stepping Stones explores the idea that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts. Simple patterns, shapes, textures, and colors are arranged in randomly selected ways. Overlaying shapes distort and blend, breaking these objects apart and causing complex forms to emerge. Combining these individual features together results in varying outcomes, from surprisingly simple to wildly chaotic.

---------------

Controls:
Press 1-6 to change the scale of the canvas (1 = default, 2500px x 2500px, 6 = 15,000px x 15,000px)
S (or double tap on mobile): Save output at current size
C: Toggle cutout shapes visibility
H: Toggle cutout outlines visibility
B: Iterate border sizes (none, default, 1.5x, 2x, 3x)
T: Toggle texture visibility
F: Toggle fullscreen
Add the url params x and y to set custom dimensions. For example, add &x=1500&y=500 for a 1500px x 500px image

---------------

Tyler Boswell (@teaboswell) 2022

metadata.name: Tangentum #236
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Trust #35
metadata.description:
Trust is an abstraction of the creative process, finding the line just before form becomes texture. Your experience with the painting requires trust; trust that something will appear from the chaos of the empty space, trust that the composition you imagine halfway through will evolve along with your ideas, and trust that the etchings lend a helping hand to the message of the piece. You may find yourself pulled left and right when decisions are made, and your interpretation at 25%, 50%, and 90% will all differ. This is what makes creating so fulfilling to me, a work of art can change course wildly from start to finish, ever molding itself until it enters the kiln.

Press ‘1’, ‘2’, or  ‘3’ to increase resolution (default is 1, higher than default may not work on certain browsers. Successfully testing in Chrome, Brave, and Opera GX with hardware acceleration enabled)

Click or tap to zoom to full res (exact zoom depends on your display)
Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle brush texture

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Kyma #240
metadata.description:
Kyma (/kee-ma/, κύμα) is a Greek word meaning wave. It is my exploration of an acoustic phenomenon known as ‘Chladni Patterns’. 

Ernst Florens Friedrich Chladni was a German physicist and musician. He was a pioneer of modern acoustics and made numerous contributions to the field. Chladni's work had a significant influence on the development of modern music theory and the technology of musical instruments. In 1787, Chladni was trying to understand how sound waves propagate and interact with objects. By vibrating a metal plate and sprinkling sand on it, he observed that the sand arranged itself into distinct patterns. These patterns are created due to the interaction between the sound waves and the plate: the sound waves cause the plate to vibrate, which in turn causes the sand to move. The sand will move away from areas of high vibration and towards areas of low vibration. This creates a unique pattern of ridges, circles, and many other shapes.

Kyma continues this study by adding color, light, and composition to the equation. Each iteration is a unique combination of two Chladni plates with different characteristics, accompanied by a palette, background lighting, and variational drawing algorithm. Plates interact with each other, forming patterns from the small detailed net-like grid to megalithic sculptures of unknown creatures and windows to another worlds.

Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Rendering can be computationally heavy, please be patient and give it some time to draw.
Chrome is highly recommended for live mode and high res saving.

Made with love, math, and p5js. 

Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2400 x 1600
[2] - save PNG 4800 x 3200
[3] - save PNG 9600 x 6400
[4] - save PNG 14400 x 9600

metadata.name: Richter #444
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

metadata.name: Resonance #233
metadata.description:
An exploration of movement, textures, chaos, order, water and fire. Discovering the breaking point in balanced shapes. Is it from nature or out of space? Resonance is a study of previously used techniques combined with Perlin noise

Press s in live mode for a download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje December 2022

metadata.name: Plottable Art Deco #59
metadata.description:
Initially made for #genuary 2023, JAN. 20 Art Deco prompt, a fxhash generator was generalized. It can yield various properties including x and y mirroring,

Meant to be plotted with a gold gel pen on a A4 dark blue paper.

"Introducing 'Plottable Art Deco', created for #genuary2023's Art Deco prompt. This fxhash generator is capable of producing unique properties such as x and y mirroring and other rare patterns, making every outcome truly one-of-a-kind. Designed to be plotted on A4 dark blue paper with a gold gel pen, this digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece.

Owning this NFT grants the right to plot or request a physical plot from the artist on https://greweb.me/plots/nft

The source code for this piece is available on GitHub at https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-artdeco, and is licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0.

metadata.name: MEGDAZ II #108
metadata.description:
Welcome to Megdaz II - one the most beautiful of all Central High Atlas area of Morocco.

I wanted to create an animated version of Megdaz - subtile movements but still interesting enough to observe the whole scene.

This artwork shows Megdaz as abstract town at different times and places:
- cafe terrace at night
- at the pool
- at the river
- before a mirror
- at the central park
- end of summer
- supper at Emmaus
- at the melting pot
- at the game

The canvas resolution is 4096x4096

--

Generative Art created by Michael Vogt (@neophob).
